public abstract class AbstractSearchSuggestGroup
extends java.lang.Object

A Grouping of Search suggest items as shown below an inputText field in Fusion Apps. This class is the default abstract implementation suitable for classic suggest items.

placeSelectedItemIdInField

public boolean placeSelectedItemIdInField()
Given placeSelectedItemInField() returns true, do we place the SearchSuggestItem id in the search field, or the display value.

It is almost always the case that the display value will be used, however it is possible to perform a transposition where the user sees one thing in the list of the suggestions, but another returned to the field.
An example of this is for typing aliases. The user may type a prefix character into the field to trigger suggest such as '#', the suggest group only responds when # is entered and it will then suggest a list of descriptive values without the '#' (they may be completely different to what is typed). When the value is selected by the user, the #value is placed in the field, not the value seen in the suggest popup.

If this is set to true and no id is set, then the display value is used as normal.
This does not apply if requiresSubmit() is true, the id is always sent in this case if it is available.

Returns:
true if to place the id and not the display value in the field when selected.
See Also:
placeSelectedItemInField(), requiresSubmit(), SearchSuggestItem

getTopSuggestions

public java.util.List<SearchSuggestItem> getTopSuggestions(java.lang.String searchText,
                                                           int maxSuggestedItems)
Get the list of top selection items.

These items are shown to the user in the search field when the user first clicks in the field, and are only shown for fnd:searchSelectBehaviors of type='popup' and topSuggestions='on'.

It is likely these items will not reflect any relation to 'searchText' which may be null, but show a simple starting list. Once the user starts to type, normal rules of getItems() will apply.

There should be no HTML markup in the individual items, bolding etc will be done by the framework. Note that there should be no assumption made that init() has been run to completion (it may be running in a background thread when this method is called, dependent on the return value of canBackgroundInit()), an empty list should be returned if no data is present.

This method is called when the user first enters the field, it MUST run quickly (< 10 msecs) and will be timed by the framework. The default implementation does nothing. Implementors should over-ride this method for their purposes.

Specified by:
getTopSuggestions in interface SearchSuggestGroup
Parameters:
searchText - text in the search field, may be null and may be ignored.
maxSuggestedItems - maximum number of suggested items to return. More can be returned but they will not be used whoever it is strongly recommended no more than this number is returned, and implementations use this number to exit the method at the first opportunity for efficienct.
Returns:
List of items so show, possibly empty but never null.

init

public void init(java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.Object> attributes)
Initialize the group, load any data as needed.

Note that this method may be run in a separate thread that has no Servlet/JSP/JSF/binding environment present, so do not rely on these. It is also quite possible, even likely (esp if init takes a while), that getItems(String, int) may be called before init() is done, so make sure getItems(String, int) can shortcut out efficiently (returning an empty list is the required functionality in this case). The default implementation. This implementation will set the suggestFieldClientId to the id of the field clicked in to initialize the suggestion.

Implementors should over-ride this method for their purposes.

Specified by:
init in interface SearchSuggestGroup
Parameters:
attributes - the attributes from fnd:searchSuggestBehavior.
See Also:
SearchSuggestGroup.canBackgroundInit(java.util.Map), SearchSuggestGroup.getItems(java.lang.String, int)

itemMatches

protected boolean itemMatches(java.lang.Object item)
Does the passed object match the rules for this suggest group. The default implementation of this method checks simply returns true, implementors should over-ride to employ their business rules. For example filter by ContextCode as returned by getContextCode() and ObjectType as returned by getObjectType(), or any other rules as they define. Implementors must ensure this is extremely performant - no database lookups etc allowed.

Parameters:
item - an object of type specific to the Group that already matches based on Object Name.
Returns:
true if this item should be used, false otherwise.

setName

public void setName(java.lang.String name)
Set the name to over-ride any coded value. The Name uniquely identifies the running instance of a group, there can only be one group with any given name running at once.

The name identifies which suggestion group a selected suggestion is posted back to when selected.

To run more than 1 suggest group of a given type, for example recent items with 2 different context/object codes, make sure the running instances of the RecentItemsSearchSuggestGroup have different names using this method. This will mean then need to be created manually without using the RecentItemsSearchSuggestGroup.NAME token.

Parameters:
name - the new name.
See Also:
getDisplayName(), getName()

getName

public void setSuggestFieldClientId(java.lang.String suggestFieldClientId)
Set the suggestFieldClient Id. This is called by the search suggest framework when suggestions are requested for a field, before the groups are polled for those suggestions. This value can be used to distinguish between multiple fields sharing the same suggestion data, perhaps different columns in a table.
